{"parse":{"title":"Duodrama","pageid":21947169,"revid":784261993,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>A <b>duodrama</b> is a theatrical <a href=\"/wiki/Melodrama\" title=\"Melodrama\">melodrama</a> for two <a href=\"/wiki/Actor\" title=\"Actor\">actors</a> or singers, in which the spoken voice is used with a musical accompaniment for heightened dramatic effect. It was popular at the end of the 18th and the beginning of the 19th century.\n</p><p>Closely related to <a href=\"/wiki/Opera\" title=\"Opera\">opera</a>, the most famous example were the 1775 works <i><a href=\"/wiki/Ariadne_auf_Naxos_(Benda)\" title=\"Ariadne auf Naxos (Benda)\">Ariadne auf Naxos</a></i> and <i><a href=\"/wiki/Medea_(Benda)\" title=\"Medea (Benda)\">Medea</a></i> by <a href=\"/wiki/Georg_Benda\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Georg Benda\">Georg Benda</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/Mozart\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mozart\">Mozart</a> admired Benda's work and used similar techniques in <i><a href=\"/wiki/Zaide\" title=\"Zaide\">Zaide</a></i> (1780) and <i><a href=\"/wiki/Thamos,_K%C3%B6nig_in_%C3%84gypten\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Thamos, K\u00f6nig in \u00c4gypten\">Thamos, K\u00f6nig in \u00c4gypten</a></i> (c. 1773-1780). He considered writing a duodrama himself, to be called <i>Semiramis</i>. <a href=\"/wiki/Beethoven\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Beethoven\">Beethoven</a>'s <i><a href=\"/wiki/Fidelio\" title=\"Fidelio\">Fidelio</a></i> (1805-1814) and <a href=\"/wiki/Carl_Maria_von_Weber\" title=\"Carl Maria von Weber\">Carl Maria von Weber</a>'s <i><a href=\"/wiki/Der_Freisch%C3%BCtz\" title=\"Der Freisch\u00fctz\">Der Freisch\u00fctz</a></i> (1821) also contain duodramas. The style is also used in <a href=\"/wiki/Lieder\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Lieder\">lieder</a> and song. <sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Duodrama&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Monodrama\" title=\"Monodrama\">Monodrama</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Melodrama\" title=\"Melodrama\">Melodrama</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Duodrama&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Warrack, John and West, Ewan (1992), <i>The Oxford Dictionary of Opera</i>, 782 pages,  <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-19-869164-5\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-19-869164-5\">0-19-869164-5</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<div role=\"navigation\" class=\"navbox\" aria-labelledby=\"Opera_terms_by_origin\" style=\"padding:3px\"><table class=\"nowraplinks collapsible autocollapse navbox-inner\" style=\"border-spacing:0;background:transparent;color:inherit\"><tbody><tr><th scope=\"col\" class=\"navbox-title\" colspan=\"2\"><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template:Opera_terms\" title=\"Template:Opera terms\"><abbr title=\"View this template\" style=\";;background:none transparent;border:none;-moz-box-shadow:none;-webkit-box-shadow:none;box-shadow:none; padding:0;\">v</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-talk\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template_talk:Opera_terms\" title=\"Template talk:Op